<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">June 19, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Rewrote the flagship dog-breeding-software comparison page to outflank BreederBuddy on the commercial-intent queries the page already ranks for.</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      <strong>Why.</strong> 28-day GSC pull ending 2026-06-16: <code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> earned 402 impressions and 1 click at average position 16-18 across 14 ranking queries (best dog breeding software, dog breeder software, breeder management software, and ~12 others). The page ranks. The page does not convert. BreederBuddy is the competitor winning the clicks: ~3,500-word homepage, six JSON-LD blocks, visible $29.99/mo pricing, and a "the all-in-one software built for serious dog breeders" frame.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What changed.</strong>
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
      <li><strong>H1 refreshed</strong> from "The Best Dog Breeding Software in 2026: A Working Breeder&apos;s Comparison" to <em>"The Best Dog Breeding Software in 2026 (Compared by a Real Breeder)"</em> — exact-match alignment with the meta title rewritten on 2026-06-19 and tighter alignment with the head-term query.</li>
      <li><strong>TL;DR rewritten</strong> as a five-bullet verdict-by-program-size block (working program → BreederHQ, single-species → BreederBuddy, lowest-price multi-species → Breeder Cloud Pro, hobby → Breedera, pedigree-club → ZooEasy/Kintraks/PedFast). Anchor links jump to each vendor section.</li>
      <li><strong>BreederBuddy added</strong> to the ItemList schema (numberOfItems 7 → 8), the side-by-side pricing table, the workflow matrix, the individual breakdowns, the "best for by breeder type" section, the mobile experience table, and the pros/cons section. Honest framing throughout: where BreederBuddy is the right pick (single-species dog or cat, predictable flat price, no marketplace needed) and where BreederHQ pulls ahead (free tier, 9 species, marketplace, OFA Sync, CHIC Readiness, Volhard/Gun Dog scoring, Scout AI).</li>
      <li><strong>New side-by-side table</strong> with pricing + free tier + species count + buyer portal + marketplace + mobile-first columns. Pricing is publicly verified per vendor: BreederBuddy $29.99/mo, Breeder Cloud Pro $6.99 Standard / $13.99 Pro, Dog Breeder Pro "Unpublished (gated)," BreederHQ free tier with paid tiers on pricing page.</li>
      <li><strong>Workflow matrix expanded</strong> from 17 rows to 20, adding three rows that separate the comparison: OFA auto-sync (BreederHQ only), CHIC readiness by breed (BreederHQ only), and temperament testing (BreederHQ only — Volhard PAT, Gun Dog Aptitude, working-dog role suitability).</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-species count is now explicit:</strong> 9 species for BreederHQ (dogs, cats, horses, goats, rabbits, sheep, alpacas, llamas, cattle); 2 for BreederBuddy (dog or cat per account); 7 claimed for Breeder Cloud Pro; 1 (with separate Cat Breeder Pro product) for Dog Breeder Pro.</li>
      <li><strong>Schema stack expanded:</strong> page now emits Article + ItemList + SoftwareApplication (page-specific, with detailed BreederHQ featureList) + FAQPage (auto-emitted by BaseLayout from the <code>faqs</code> prop, which grew from 12 to 14 entries including direct "How does BreederHQ compare to BreederBuddy" and "How does BreederHQ compare to Breeder Cloud Pro" answers). BreadcrumbList and the site-wide SoftwareApplication continue to come from BaseLayout.</li>
      <li><strong>BreederHQ breakdown deepened:</strong> OFA Sync, CHIC Readiness Widget, Volhard PAT scoring, Gun Dog Aptitude scoring, working-dog role suitability, Scout AI document extraction, and the 9-species claim are now called out by name in the BreederHQ section so the schema-and-prose tell the same story.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <strong>What did NOT change.</strong> No invented customer numbers (BreederBuddy is leading with placeholder-looking "0+" stats; we declined to compete on fake metrics). No "verified breeder" or "verified directory" language. No em dashes. Existing Article schema preserved with bumped <code>dateModified</code>. Existing workflow visual + "what makes great dog breeding software" rubric + decision rubric all preserved. Tone unchanged.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Visible body word count:</strong> ~3,200-3,500 (matching BreederBuddy depth). Schema blocks on the page: 5 (Article, ItemList, SoftwareApplication page-specific, FAQPage, BreadcrumbList) plus the site-wide SoftwareApplication from BaseLayout.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Strongest claims against BreederBuddy:</strong> (1) BreederHQ has a free tier with no time limit; BreederBuddy has no free tier at all. (2) BreederHQ runs 9 species in one account; BreederBuddy runs dog OR cat in one account. (3) BreederHQ includes a public buyer-facing marketplace (marketplace.breederhq.com) that buyers actively search; BreederBuddy&apos;s website add-on is a private storefront, not a discovery channel.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Success criteria at 4 weeks.</strong> GSC: average position 16-18 → 8-12 across the 14 ranking queries; clicks-per-week from &lt;1 to 5-10. If both move, depth-and-comparison was the right play. If neither moves, the problem is domain authority and a different lever is required.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>
